Sunday, January 1,1939

Worked all day until late in the evening on the correlation of L and F, and H and F, Platteville series only. Made good progress, but these tabulations and calculations are certainly time-consuming.

Red Rattler reported by me and the boys at the reptile club. Kearny Mesa.

Monday, January 2, 1939

Worked all day and evening today - first on the fang correlations and regression lines which didn't go so well, then on the census for 1938 which is now completed, and forms the final table in the collecting study. This took a lot of work.

------------------------

(May 6, continued)

1 Arizona L DOR Date City Fields
1 gopher M DOR Holtville Fields
1 gopher S DOR Holtville Fields (saved)
Stopped for a Choc-Malt at Holtville; then turned north to Calipatria and Niland. Left Holtville at 1:10. Warm 86 degrees and very windy.

1 gopher S DOR Holtville Fields
1 gopher S DOR Holtville Fields
1 gopher S DOR Calipatria Fields
1 gopher L DOR Calipatria Fields
1 gopher L DOR Calipatria Fields
1 gopher L DOR Calipatria Fields

Niland at 2:10. From here on we went around the north-east side of Salton Sea. Held up by Arizona Police looking for a murderer at Pope.

1 dip L DOR at Durmid, Riverside County. Low brush.
1 Arizona L DOR Salton, Riverside County. Low brush desert (saved)
dip seen at Montmar
(Continued on Jan. 3rd)

  • lwilliams 03/22/2012 12:43 PM

  • Mary Miller 03/20/2012 12:33 AM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:37 PM

Tuesday, January 3, 1939

Company at dinner tonight; nothing done.

---------------------------

(May 6 continued from Jan 2)

whiptail and Uta stans seen at Mortmar. Caught a gopher alive at Mecca. He was crossing the road at 3:40 pm. Warm and windy. Reached Indio at 4:10. Blowing very hard. Much dust. Had a hard time deciding what to do next because of the unfortunate weather. Decided to go on toward Palm Springs.

1 Mitch M DOR Cathedral City. Brushy desert with rocky hills 100 ft. away.

Had supper at Whitewater. Thought some of going up toward 29 Palms but finally decided to try the aqueduct road. Left Whitewater and reached Garnet at 6:15. Blowing a gale and already quite cold. A rotten night.

Went up several side canyons without any luck. Reached the head of Pushawalla Canyon at 7:15. 68 degrees. A little breeze. Not quite dark. There was a little breeze at the canyon heads, but much wind and colder out on the main road.

1 Trimorphodon COR 7:25, 62 degrees (corrected). Wind blowing a gale. Brushy desert.

Practically dark. This was between

(Continued on Jan 4)

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 03/30/2012 01:08 PM

Wednesday, January 4, 1939

Conferred with Mrs. Leslie at noon; started her tabulating the long lengths of lucasensis series.
Gene Fisher came over today with two sample pages of the night collecting paper; also one of the tables. Discussed details.

---------------------------

)May 6 Cont from Jan 3d)

Pushawalla and Berdoo Canyon brahces.
1 Coleonyx COR Berdoo Canyon 7:45, 66 degrees blowing a gale
1 Coleonyx COR Berdoo Canyon 8:15 66 degrees gale
1 Coleonyx COR Fargo Canyon 8:45 64 degrees gale

Found a pair of sidewinders mating on the road (branch to Fargo Canyon at 8:50. Strong wind blowing 64 degrees. Dark. Although placed in the box carefully they were separated when we reached Indio

1 sidewinder COR 8:5 64 degrees 2 mi up the same Fargo branch. Very windy.

Reached Indio at 9:20. A very strong wind blowing (blew all night). Cold. Much dust flying. An impossible night. No moon up to this time. Found a good auto court.

Total miles today 246. Miles evening hunt 27. Miles in Imperial County irrigated territory 84.

What luck to have such lovely weather.

Chas Shaw Worked today. Slept in house.

Thursday, January 5, 1939

Devel worked on worm snakes today.
Worked on accounts tonight.

---------------------------

(May 7th Continued)

1 gopher S. DOR Warners grass
1 pacific garter DOR 3 mi E of Hot Springs Hotel. Grass. Plenty red.
1 H.T. DOR Moretti's.
1 banded racer L DOR Moretti's Field grass
1 boyle's king M DOR Foster Saved. Fields
1 band racer M DOR San Diego Brush

Total miles today 146; San Diego County 87

Chas Shaw worked today
Gander reports a live patch-nose on the road at Moretti's :30 am

---------------------------

Jim Devel's Report (already entered in census)

1 R. lecontei 2 mi W. of The Narrows 7:57 pm
1 A.e. occidentalis 1 mi W. of The Narrows DOR
1 S. occipitalis 1 mi E of The Narrows DOR
1 T. vandenburghi The Narrows DOR
1 S. occupitalis 1 mi W of The Narrows DOR
1 P.d. perkinsi 4 mi W of The Narrows 8:58
1 A.e. occidentalis 5 mi W of The Narrows 9:02
1 R. lecontei 6 mi W of The Narrows 9:07
1 L. r. roseofusca Yaqui Well DOR
1 T. o. hammondii Sentenac Canyon DOR
1 H. ochrorhynchus Sentenac Canyon DOR

(also 13 geckos)

Friday, January 6, 1939

A little work on intraspecies fang curves tonight. Company

--------------------------

(May 12 continued)

1 Sonora L DOR Oasis saved
Reached Indio at 9 and got gas. 92 degrees. No breeze. No moon. Bufo cognatus was heard. then started around aqueduct road.

1 sidewinder COR Fargo Canyon Junction 9:40 69 degrees
1 L. gracia COR Fargo Canyon (2 1/2 from upper end) 9:50 1 degrees. A fine spec.
1 cally DOR Fargo Canyon
1 platyrhinos DOR Fargo Canyon Junction
1 Coleonyx SOR Fargo Canyon Junction
A little breeze in evidence now out on the main road. Getting cooler.
1 L. gracia COR Berdoo Canyon branch 1 mi from the junction. 10:17 71 degrees.
1 platyrhinos asleep on the road 1 mi NW of Berdoo Canyon Junction 10:40. Both of these were so flat on the road that they appeared dead.
Tried both Pushawalla and Fran Hill branches without success. Passed up the others because it was so late.

(continued on Jan 7)

Saturday, January 7, 1939

Worked all day on intraspecies fang curves, their equations and suitabilities and made fair progress at least in visualizing the problems.
Out to dinner tonight.

--------------------------

(May 12 Continued from Jan 6th)

1 Coleonyx at Pushawalla Junction
1 spotted nite COR Fan Hill Canyon Junction 11:05 somewhat breezy. 64 degrees F.
1 leafnose COR 1000 Palms Canyon Junction 11:20 62 degrees F Breezy.
1 ? LOR (Probably leaf nose at Wide Canyon Junction. 11:35
1 platyrhinos DOR Wide Canyon Junction.

Reaching Banning at 12:25. Now very windy and cold. Drove fast from Garnett to Banning and may have passed up DORs. This mileage should not be counted as part of evening desert drive.

Total miles today 233
Miles in San Diego County. All daylight 97
Miles of evening desert hunt {S.D.) Coline to Garnett 117.

A fairly good evening; having in mind the lateness of the hour when we reached good territory (the aqueduct road). The boas were the cream of the hunt.

Sunday, January 8, 1939

Worked all day and late into the evening on the fang correlations. Made some progress - not as fast as I had hoped.

---------------------------

(May 13th continued)

We hunted at one or two points in the Morongo Valley for a few moments, but got nothing. 1 X.v. got away. We left the paved highway and went north from Warren's Well (just east of Lone Star) at 10:35. Hunted 2 mi N. of Warren's Well and got a few lizards. This a rocky area. Lizards not very plentiful. It was cool and breezy and part overcast.

1 platyrhinos DOR 3 mi E. of Rock Corral
Hunted at this point and got several lizards. Cool, breezy and overcast. Got a large magister 2 mi N of Rock Corral.
2 Large leopard lizards DOR 3 mi NE of Rock Corral.
Now becoming increasingly cloudy and threatening.
chuckwalla lost in the rocks 3 mi E of Lucerne. This was at 1:50.
platyrhinos DOR at this point.
leopard lizard and whiptail DOR

(continued on Jan 9)

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 03/30/2012 01:34 PM
  • Mary Miller 03/25/2012 08:51 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:37 PM

Monday, January 9, 1939

leopard lizard, Emigrant Wash, Death Valley, J. Dixon, September 21, 2938

Meeting of NH Fellows tonight. A little miscellaneous work tonight.

--------------------------

(May 13 Continued from Jan 8)

at Dead Man's Point.
Reached Victorville at 2:30. It was cool and sprinkling. Forgot to get gas very foolishly. Had a good ice cream drink.
1 gopher S DOR 3 mi E of Adelanto thin brushy desert.
1 platyrhinos DOR 5 mi N of Adelanto
2 callys DOR 7 mi N. of Adelanto.
More sprinkles and wind.
1 red racer M DOR 9 mi N. of Adelanto brushy desert.
1 gopher M DOR Kramer Hills brushy desert.
After leaving Kramer, west bound it began to rain hard. Also we discovered we were practically out of gas and there are no stations along here. Much worried we passed up 1 DOR snake probably a scute. However we arrived at Mojave ok with one gallon to spare. this was a close squeak. Left at 4:30; cold and rainy.

From Mojave to Bakersfield was a tough drive. Very heavy rain. Much

(continued on Jan 10)

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 03/30/2012 01:35 PM
  • Mary Miller 03/25/2012 08:59 PM
  • BPOC 12/07/2010 05:37 PM

Tuesday, January 10, 1939

Got the first 12 galleys of the night collecting paper today. also the separates of the last paper in Copeia.

Movie tonight: The Grand Illusion

rain nearly all the way. Creeks flooded. Some sleet and road slippery at Monolith. A car over the hill near Bakersfield. Raining hard at Bakersfield.

1 gopher L DOR Trees and grass 2 mi S. of Ilmon

We got a meal and put up. I tried hard to go through to SF tonight but a/c station not being open until 8 after we had left LA the complications re accommodations were too difficult, so gave it up. Wrote diary and turned in at 10.

Miles today 247. A tough and fruitless day because unseasonable weather.

Wednesday, January 11, 1939

Read proof today - quite clean. Got 2 more galleys completing Part 1 except tables.

Worked on F-H, F-L correlations tonight.

-------------------------
(May 14 continued)

Many toads B.b. halophilus DOR 11 mi N. of Small's Corner = 2 mi S. of King's County line on road to Corcoran.
Got 3 live C. silus and 1 DOR on Corcoran Road 2 mi N. of King's Co line in a barren field. This 5 mi S.W. of Atwell, Kings County.
Bufo noted 4 mi S of Corcoran, King's Co
1 gopher M DOR 5 mi W. of Corcoran, King's Co Fields
1 boyles K L DOR Guernsey, King's Co grass
1 gopher M DOR Guernsey, King's Co, grass
1 gopher M DOR Hanford, King's Co, gardens
1 gopher M DOR Laton, Fresno Co, grass
1 longnose M DOR Laton Fresno Co grass
(plenty of red)
toads noted at Fowler, Fresno Co
1 gopher M DOR Malaga Fresno Co fields
Reached Fresno at 4;30. Warm and very sultry. Gander reports a hard shower at sunset. I caught the train to SF at 6:17.

Miles today 190. Reached SF at 10:30 and went up to the Fairmont

Thursday, January 12, 1939

Jim Devel worked on worm snakes today.
Worked on equations tonight.

---------------------------

(May 15 continued)

2 rattlers DOR Reward, Kern Co, fields.
1 gopher L DOR 2 mi S. of McKittrick, Ken Co thin brush
1 red racer L DOR 4 mi SE of McKittrick, Ken Co grass
1 gopher S DOR Fellows thin brush, saved head. Left Taft at 8:10. 7:40 sky clear.
Beginning of evening drive.
1 Arizona COR 8:35, 70 degrees F, windy 10 mi E. of Maricopa Junction at 9:15. 68 degrees F.

Reached Bakersfield at 9:45.
Miles today 274; evening drive 53.

Friday, January 13, 1939

Rec'd today the proofs of the tables and the second revision of the proofs of Part I text.
Company tonight.

-------------------------
(May 16 continued)

Toads DOR at Weed Patch.
1 gopher L DOR Weed Patch fields.
Evening drive.
Left Bakersfield at 6:30. Temp 73 degrees; breezy thin clouds. No moon. 69 degrees at sunset.
1 gopher S DOR field - mesquite Old River, Kern Co saved head.
1 gopher L DOR Elk Hills, Kern Co, grass
1 red racer S DOR Elk Hills, Kern Co
1 rattler S DOR Elk Hills, Kern Co]] Saved.
toads collected 3 mi S. of Bowerbank, Kern Co.
1 Arizona DOR saved Rosedale, Kern Co
Reached Bakersfield at 9:30 62 degrees
Too cold for good hunting.
Miles today 206; evening drive 54
(after sunset)

Saturday, January 14, 1939

Worked hard all day and evening but didn't make the progress I had hoped. Did get the worm snakes entered in the big sheets up to date including color notes. But the fang statistics went very slowly. Planned the figured.

(May 17 continued)

1 Anniella |DOR| strand, Kern Co. Cottonwood flat.
1 Gopher M |DOR| strand, Kern Co. grass and mesquite
1 Gopher L |DOR| strand, Kern, Co. grass and mesquite

Skelly observed 3 mi. W.g Stevens.

1 Gopher S |DOR| Bena, grass saved
1 Gopher S |DOR| Lemon, grass and brush.
1 Gopher L |DOR| Lemon, grass hills
1 Gopher M |COR| Lemon, grassy hills 5:17 PM
1 Gopher L |DOR| Weed Patch Field - vineyard.
1 Toad |COR| Stevens 7:40 61°
1 Arizona L |COR\ 7 mi W. of Old RIver, Kern Co, 64°, 8 P.M.

Returned to Bakersfield at 8:55. Many excellent roads, but too cool for night collecting. Miles today 171; evening drive 32.

Notes:

Sunday, January 15, 1939

Worked all day and late into the evening on the fang computations. Made some good progress.

(May 20 continued)

1 Red Racer L |DOR| Elsinore grass.
1 Red Racer L |DOR| North Elsinore rock and light brush
1 Horned Toad |DOR| 2 mi W.g Perris
1 Horned Toad |DOR| Romoland, Riverside, CA
1 Horned Toad |DOR| 4 mil W.g Ribbonwood
1 Horned Toad |DOR| 2 mi W.g Ribbonwood (saved)

Reached Indio at 6:10 PM; warm and very windy. Partly couldy. Started out again on the aqueduct road at 6:45. Dusk. New Moon. Blowing very hard. Warm. Windy. Passed up Fargo branch. Next went up Berdoo Canyon branch 7 to 7:25. Didn't see a thing. Not quite dark. Next tried Pushawalla canyon 7:35 to 7:50. Nothing. Now dark 7:20 at Pushawalla junction.
Very strong wind out in the unprotected ; fairly quiet up the canyons.

1 leaf nose COR 1 mi NW g Pushawalla junct. 7:56, 68°, strong wind. Dark at last Call this Pushawalla Canyon.
Next tried the Fan Hill Branch. 1 mi. from the junction (on the way mt) got 2 leaf noses almost 100 ft. apart.

(continued on Jan. 16)

Notes:

Monday, January 16, 1939

Went to the reptile club tonight. Announced the outcome of the contest for 1938

Shaw 95
Miss Sprague 79
Deuel 30

(May 20th, Continued from Jan. 15)

1 Leaf nose |COR| Fan Hill Canyon 8:17; 68°
1 Leaf nose |COR| Fan Hill Canyon 8:18; 68°
1 Sidewinder |COR| on the main road 2 mi S.E. of Wide Canyon Junction 8:35; a hard wind blowing, 67°

Drove up Wide Canyon. Then turned and drove back very fast to Berdoo Canyon Junction hoping to find a more protected area for the wind was very bad nearer San Gorgonio. Might have missed something on this trip (14 miles); wouldn't have missed anything large. Started up Berdoo canyon at 9:10.

1 Leaf nose |COR| at entrance to this road 9:11; 73 degrees Fahrenheit
1 spotted night |COR| 9:30; 72 degrees Fahrenheit medium breeze 1 mi inside the junction.

Next tried Fargo Canyon 9:42 to 10:10. Not a thing seen. Too cold and windy. Then drove fast back to Berdoo Canyon

(Continued on Jan. 17)

Tuesday, January 17, 1939

Got the proof of part 2 today.
Worked on accounts and proof reading tonight.

(May 20th continued from Jan. 16)

1 Leaf nose |COR| 2 mi up from Junction of Berdoo Canyon (in the Canyon) 10:25; 72°
1 Leaf nose |DOR| Indio saved.

Returned to Indio 11. Warmer and a little less wind. 70°. Turned in.

Total miles today 288 miles in San Diego, CA. 54 (all daylight). Night hunt 95 miles. This included 18 miles driving fast. 4:25 hours in the night hunt.

7 live snakes - 1 |DOR|

• Wednesday, January 18, 1939

AIEE organization meeting tonight.
Still working on collecting paper proofs.

(May 21 continued)

1 Red Racer L |DOR| Gilman Hot Springs Field St. Branch
1 Red Racer L |DOR| Gilman Hot Springs Field St. Branch

Had lunch at Hemet at 1:30.

1 med gopher |DOR| Egan (Santa Fe siding)Fields
1 garter M. |DOR| Temecula Fields
1 Lateralis L |DOR| Temecula grade brush Sawed Head
1 Boyles K L |DOR| Temecula grade brush trees
1 Boyles K L |DOR| Poway grass

Arrived at home at 4 P.M. cool and windy; clear
Miles today 171. Again a very disappointing list of DORs. Evidently the boys haven't been out lately. Chris worked for two hours after we returned. The basement is full of specimens awaiting attention. Miscellaneous catching up tonight.

Thursday, January 19, 1939

Received the last of the first galleys of the collecting paper today.

Concert tonight.

(May 27th Continued)

2 Gophers L |DOR| Perris Fields
1 Trimorphodon S |DOR| Box Spring Geode. Brush Rocks
1 Red Racer M |DOR| Verdemont, S.B. Co. Light Brush.

These two snakes were together. The live one over the dead one. Trying to mate?

1 Coleonyx |COR| 8:52, Pisgha, 73°

From here on it was alternately warm and cool depending on the altitude. Little breeze; more than 1/2 moon. While we traveled fast, we certainly missed no large snake and probably no small ones. May have passed up a Coleonyx or two. Don't know why they were so plentiful at first but not later. They weren't out or we would have seen DORs for there was plenty of traffic.

Reached Needles at 11:30 PM. Warm quiet. The boys went out for Toads and insects which they got, but 2 was very tired and turned in. Miles today 347; S.D.Co, 70°. Evening drive Barstow-Needles 147.

At 1:30 after pickling all shot specs. It was hot with scattered clouds.

1 Patchnose M |DOR| Louise. Very Light Brush

Also secured other lizards which were preserved. The rocks are too hard for the best results although they have some flakes. Returned and hunted at Hackberry. Got a few lizards here but no Xantusia. The rocks are poor here. There are better ones between Hackberry and Valentine. Returned to Kingman at 4:30.

Wednesday, January 25, 1939

Chas. Shaw worked on fangs today. Bob Hoard called today and took photographs.

(May 29 Continued)

We found grater showing a freshly killed rattler to the CCC boys. It was a fine specimen (a pyrrhus - Stephensi intergrade). Which has been caught alive that morning but had died from the heat. It had eaten a full grown Cnemidophorus.
We next went back up to Grater's office and went over his specimens - that is the one lately acquired since I had identified his collection. He gave me a number of his specimens including more rattlers, 2 , and a Trimorphodon proving once more the statement that the place to hunt is in someone else's laboratory.

He had a number of newer and interesting records. One rattler a pyrrhus from Fortification Hill near Kingman Wash contained a chuck. Gila monsters have been collected at Pierce's Ferry and Emery Falls (4 mi. inside of Grand Canyon). L.g. Boylii at Searchlight. Sidewinders have been taken at Boulder.

(Continued on Jan. 26)

Szlyna

Thursday, January 26, 1939

Done tabulating tonight. Also checking proof again.

(May 29 Cont. from Jan. 25)

City, up by the water tank.

While taking leave of Grater we were shown a telegram from the Hall that Dr. Joseph Grinnell had died. This was sad news and did a great to zoology. A more thorough careful and enthusiastic worker I never knew. He was responsible for the height stander of MVZ and a whole generation of important zoologists.

We left Boulder City at 2:45 and Las Vegas at 3:25. This was later then I had hoped to get away but the visit to Grater was certainly worth while. It was very hot as we pulled out.

Saturday, February 4, 1939

Worked in the early morning checking the paper proof. Then checked the specimens sent for identification by the Boulder Dam Recreation Area.

Spent the rest of the day and until midnight on the fang calculations. Seem to be doing it over and over. Don't think I ever wasted so much time on a repeated curve drawing and calculation. At any rate it is getting more logical and coordinated. Hope this is the last time the ax2+bx+C curves have to be recalculated.

Chas Shaw worked today on rattler counts.

A damaged S. Occipitalis from the Boulder Dam area. Body rings 31, tail 10, No. 17 is the first to cross the belly. Bards wider than the interspaces.

Friday, February 10, 1939

Electrical Meeting tonight

(June 10 Continued)

1 Arizona M |DOR| Whitewater. Rocky wash
1 Sonora L |DOR| Edom Brushy desert.
Light brown rings on a white background.

Returned to the auto camp and waited for Chuck to come to life. Had breakfast and went out to scout the aqueduct road at 8:40. It was already quite hot. Notes on the road and its branches are as follows: The main road starts low at 60-70 but goes up quite high then low again at the garnet. Thus there are a variety of burdening areas - some sandy, some brushy, some cactus. No rock cliffs on the main road but plenty of scattered boulders at various points.

The branches are as follows: Fargo, a long run up an alluvial fan; then a sandy, rocky creek bed. The actual canyon part is quite short.
Berdoo. Short entrance cone; then a canyon with a winding rock-strewn river bed on one side and rocky cliffs on the other. No flaking rocks.
Looks like the best canyon for rock -

(Continued on Feb. 11)

inhabiting forms.

Fan Hill. The Road is rather good; mostly greasewood and boulders. It is higher than the others as the main road has been coming up a long slope.

1000 Palms. The road is unpaved so we didn't explore.

Wide Canyon. This is a brush covered

fan. There is no true canyon.

Long Canyon. Unpaved and unexplored.

Little Morongo. This is the longest side road of all. The pavement has been washed in several places. The fan is somewhat lower and more barren than the others (hence the sidewinders that evening). The brush gets heavier as one goes further in. The canyon part is short, but there is some.
Altogether these side roads share some mighty good territory, much like Borego. Many scattered boulders, light and heavy

Monday, February 13, 1939

People in to dinner tonight. Read Mexican rattlesnakes from USNM arrived today.

(June 10 Cont. from Feb. 12)

brush, a little side canyon work (but no granite) washes, some cactus. The total distance from the point where you leave US 60-70 to garnet including all paved branches is just 70 miles. The reptiles taken on this morning exploratory trip were as follows (it was a mighty morning); we started at 8:40.

1 Sidewinder M |DOR| Indo. Sandy desert (was at beginning of aqueduct road) dips and callies were exceedingly plentiful at the entrance to Fargo branch.
Watching them run down the road it was noted that dips run on all 4 legs, but one was seen to run on 2. Many were perched on rocks. Observing callies run away up a paved road I would say the tails are not curved over the back. Got a leopard lizard on the Fargo branch. Dips were seen well up into Fargo; then chucks several of which were collected.

(Continued on Feb. 14)

Tuesday, February 14, 1939

Out to dinner tonight.

(June 10 cont. from Feb. 13)

In this and other canyons (including Berdoo) the chucks were often on the rounded stream - bed boulders, not on cliffs.

Hunted in sand dunes between Fargo and Berdoo junctions. Collected 2 dips; callies and whips were seen.
Chucks were plentiful up in Berdoo canyon; we collected only 1 or 2.
A chuck was seen in the Pushawalla branch. It was windy on this fan. Callies were seen and a few dips, but they were now less common.

Got a leopard lizard in Fan Hill, a female with orange, but seemed thin as if the eggs had been laid.

Dips were seen between 1000 Palms and Wide Canyon junctions. Also callies. Just north of Long Canyon Junction two dips were mating on the highway at 11:45. Hot and windy. The male was on top, his head slightly to the rear, with tail curled under hers. They broke away suddenly when frightened. We collected the male. Callies were seen here. Also at Little

1 Pyrrhus L |COR| 5 mi. up Fargo Canyon from the junction; practically the head of the canyon. Dusk 7:18; 85°; rocky creek bed. Our attention was drawn to him as he rattled as we passed although he was by the side of the road in the rock - not on the road. Monday, February 20, 1939

F.N. Cox of Berkeley wrote that he has evidence that a sea-snake was taken 5 years ago off San Clemente. Went to the reptile club tonight; not very much interesting discussion. They doubt Cox's record above.
Went up to the zoo with Perkins to look at eye shine. It was very strong in a large toad; noticeable in a number of snakes including Crotalus. That is we got an observable glow with flash lights - not just a reflection from the eyeball. Question is - what is eye shine? Whether it is present in reptiles depends on the definition.

Thursday, February 23, 1939

Today received the first preliminary copy of the "Studies of Reptile Life in the Arid Southwest" Looks okay.

(June 11 Continued)

1 Gopher S |DOR| Victorville scattered brush and fields
1 Drip seen 15 mi. S. of Kramer Junct.
1 Cally seen 10 mi. S. of Kramer Junct.

Reached Atolia at 1:57.
Hunted a few moments in Lara Mts. (Chuck did while I slept) saw nothing but utas. Then came on to Trona where we arrived at 4 P.M. Very hot.
After having a drink we went up to an oil station and examined our specimens. This was at 10 to 5 as I had spent some time writing in this diary. We found that the snakes had been overheated and nearly all were dead. The dead included the two large mitches, the coleonyx, most of the sonoras and leaf-noses, 1 worm out of 5 (we had wet their nose) 1 sidewinder out of 3, both Arizona's etc. We worked until 7, preserving these specimens, handicapped by lack of bottles and other facilities and surrounded by a large and admiring crowd. We doubted

specimens until 12:45. There was much to do because of the debacle at Trona.

Sunday, April 23, 1939

Bloomfield worked somewhat over 4 hours on scale counts today. Spent the morning on statistical forms and miscellaneous checking of specimens. Company for lunch. Had a medium boa bitten by a rattler (I presume). His head and neck swelled up greatly. Still alive 7-8-39.

Shaw and Bloomfield caught 20 Annillas on Coronado strand by hard digging. Particularly good to dig under verbena bushes.

Stopping quickly enough.

1 Long-nose L |DOR| Winterhaven (saved)

Saturday, May 6, 1939

This morning we left Yuma at 8:50. It was cool, sunny, and breezy. Some clouds to the south east. We first drove to Araz looking for the road to Imperial dam which we missed; then back to Winterhaven, where we found the branch 3/4 of a mile east toward Yuma. Then went up to the dam where we spent considerable time driving and looking around.

1 Gopher S |DOR| Winterhaven, Mesquite
1 Gopher S. |DOR| Winterhaven, Cultivated fields (saved).
1 Gopher M. |DOR| Winterhaven, Cult. fields
1 Yuma King S. |DOR| Bard, (very dark, narrow dark bands)
1 B. Woodhousii |DOR| Bard, Cult. fields

Left the dam southbound at 10:30 A.M. Hunted for a few moments on the edge of the sand hills 14 mi. W. of Winterhaven. Got 2 Uta Graciosa and, 1 .

The utas were on horizontal limbs of mesquite, on the tops of branches with hooks facing inward. There were 4 in one small mesquite.

1 Gopher M. |DOR| Alsmo fields (saved head)

(continued on Jan 2)

Sunday, May 7, 1939

Today Weiss and I drove home from Indio. Started at 9:05; it was warm and quiet. Arrived at 1:35; clear, cool, and breezy. Went via Palms to Pine's Highway, Anza, Cahuilla, Auguanga, Oak Grove, Warner's Hot Springs, Santa Ysabel, Ramona, El Cajon, and La Mesa.

1 Sidewinder S. junct. P to P with Palm Spr. Highway. Sandy desert.
1 Leaf-nose M. junct. P to P with Palm Spr. Highway. Sandy desert.

Collected a leopard lizard and a small dip 2 mi. up the highway from this junction. Utas and callys were also seen here. For a short distance many lizards were seen on the rocks.
Whiptail found injured on highway, saved. 5 mi. W. of Junction.
Whiptail seen 7 mi. from junction. Chucks seen 8 and 12 mi. from the junction.
First skelly seen 11 miles from the junction. They were very common from here on. Nightingales is 15 mi. from the junction and Ribbonwood 18 miles. The turn off to Anza is 25 miles.

1 H.T. |DOR| at Ribbonwood.
Skellies at Anza.
1 Long-nose M. |DOR| Auguanga, brush.
1 Red Racer L. |DOR| Oak Grove, brush.

(Continued on Jan 5th)

Friday, May 12, 1939

Went to the zoo and Natural History Museum this noon to clear up last details and get the mail. Perkins is expected back tomorrow.

At 4:15 started on a trip - objective Bakersfield - with Frank Gander. Went ont via Lakeside, Ramona, Julian, Sentenac, Dry Lake, Kane Spring, thence north on 99 to Indio. Then around the aqueduct road and up several of the side canyons. Finally ended up at Banning for the night. It was cool and overcast in San Diego and cloudy in the back country. Surprisingly however it was quite good in the desert; quite clear, warm (although not as much as we wished) and almost without wind.

1 Gopher M. |DOR| Challas Hts., grass
1 Garter M. |DOR| Lakeside, grass
1 Oreganus S. |DOR| Suthenland, trees-grass
1 Gopher S. |DOR| Suthenland, grass
1 Gopher S. |DOR| Santa Ysabel, grass
1 Alligator Lizard L |DOR| Ynola, grass-trees

Reached Scissors Crossing at sundown. Cool. Stopped a few moments to talk to Benson. It had been cool recently. He didn't have much.

1 Coleonyx |COR| 5 mi. E of Imp. Co. Line., 7:30, 74°
1 McCallii |DOR|
1 Coleonyx seen at Kane Spr. (7 mi. N.W. of)

(Cont. on Jan. 6th.)

Saturday, May 13, 1939

This morning we left Banning at 8:10. It was cool and windy. Also part cloudy. We first went 1 mi. S. of Banning, where the old road starts up the mountain. There is some fine granite here and we found X. Henshawi exceedingly plentiful. The hunting was as good as any seen anywhere in S.D. Co. They were under flakes and top rocks, not only on S. side of boulders, but other sides as well. We got a good series in a short time. I dropped my glasses; Gander found them but one of the wings had been stepped on and broke off. Went back to Banning and got some 5's and 10.

Started eastward from Banning again at 9:20, reaching 29 Palms junction at 9:42. It was cool and breezy, and we began to be much worried about the weather. Cloudy to the north about the mountains; clear to the south east.

1 Arizona L |DOR| 7 mi. N. of Palms Junction. 1800 ft. Brushy desert. Saved head.
1 Red Rattler S. |DOR| 8 mi. N. of Palms Junct. Brushy desert. This 1 mi. S. of Riverside - S. Berdoo Co. line.

Increasingly cool and cloudy here.

(Continued on Jan. 8th)

Saturday, May 20, 1939

Spent the morning on miscellaneous work and getting ready for the afternoon trip. Also went over to the zoo and participated in the oral examination of Bob Hoard for his master's degree. Saw Ray Cowles. Bloomfield worked part of the day.

In the afternoon at 1:30 Chas Shaw and I started for Indio. It was clear and warm with some breeze. As the afternoon progressed it was evident that it was going to be a very windy and rather cool night on the desert. We went via Capistrano and the Hot Springs Road across the Elsinore mts; thence to Perris and Hemet; then across the San Jacintos via the Palomar to Pines Highway; then to Indio where we secured accommodations before starting on the evening drive. The whole trip was characterized by the lack of DOR's; very few for this time of year. We watched for them carefully.

1 Red Racer M. |DOR| Las Flores, grass
1 Gopher L. |DOR| Agra, grass
1 Boyles K. L. |DOR| Doheny Park, Orange Co., grass
1 Gopher M. |DOR| Doheny Park, Orange Co., grass (Capistrano 3 PM)
1 Gopher L. |DOR| Elsinore, Light brush

(Continued on Jan. 15)

Sunday, May 21, 1939

Started home from Indio at 9:05. It was clear, warm, and breezy.

1 Arizona M. |DOR| Indio, orchards
1 Sonora L. |DOR| Indio Wells, sandy desert
1 Sonora L. |DOR| Date Gardens, sandy desert,date groves saved.
1 Dip |DOR| Junction Palm Springs and P to P highway
1 Dip |DOR| Cathedral City.
1 Leopard Lizard |DOR| Palm Springs
1 Dip |SOR| Palm Springs
1 Arizona S. |DOR| Whitewater, brush.

Saw Allmans show to the west of Bamming. He tells many wild tales in describing his snakes. Only one item worth while. Oreganus is found at this point. The show is fairly good although nothing rare. This is near the S.P. Siding called Owl.

We arrived at Banning at 10:30 and went to the rocks 1 1/2 mile south where we hunted until 12:10. Got a number of Xantusia Henshawi. Also chuck got a fine large C.M. Pyrrhus. Shot a few skellies and utas. Whiptails and orcuttis were seen. One of the latter was found dead and saved.

1 Red Racer L. |DOR| Lamb Canyon, heavy brush
1 Sateralis L. |DOR| Lamb Canyon, light brush

Lamb Canyon is a short cut to San Jacinto.

Sunday, May 28, 1939

Awake at 6:15; up at 7 and brought diary down to date. Started from Needles at 8:55; clear and hot. Said to have been 110° last two days here.

Dipsosaurus was active at Needles at 8.
1 Leopard Lizard (with orange color) |DOR| at Blythe road junction, 6 mi. S. of Needles, rocky desert.
Callisaurus observed 12 mi. S. of Needles. (Beal). Reached Topock at 9:25.
Dipsoaurus noted 2, 3, and 5 mi. N. of Topock; rocky and sandy desert. But the lizards were not nearly as common here as on a former trip.

Collard lizards were collected 9 and 10 mi. N. of Topock in lava rock. One was noted standing with straightened legs to avoid the hot rock.
Dip noted 10 mi. N. of Topock, lava rock.
Uta stans 12 mi. N. of Topock, rocky desert.
Collared lizard 13 mi. N. of Topock. rocky desert.

First chuck seen 16 mi. N. of Topock amid scattered lava boulders 17 mi. N. of Topock, caught 2 chucks (1 small) and 1 collared lizard. Scattered rocks.

Monday, May 29, 1939

Awake at 6:35; up at 7 and brought diary down to date. This took an hour.
Woke the boys up.

Left Las Vegas at 9:15 for Boulder City and Boulder Dam. It was partly cloudy and hot. Just before Railroad Pass and at the Pass callies were seen and collected on scattered boulders. One whiptail was seen.

Spent from 10 AM to 12:10 going through the power plant with H.O. Watts. The most thorough inspection I have ever made. We then returned to Boulder City where we had lunch at the Green Hut. The choc-malt wasn't as good as some we have had.

Went to the Park Service Museum and sat around waiting for Grater which we did for almost half an hour until someone told us that he was down where a new beach was being constructed by the CCC and might not be back in the afternoon at all.

The time we went and had some difficulty finding the place. Finally located it and Grater to the north of the present landing. But still in Hemenway wash.

(Continued on Jan. 25)

Thursday, June 8, 1939

Leroy Arnold called today. Talked over his project with him and identified a few reptiles for him.

Friday, June 9, 1939

Today Chas. Shaw and I left for a desert trip at 5:25 in the afternoon. It was clear and warm. We had loaded the car at noon. We went ont to Borego and Indio via Fletcher Hills and the usual route to Julian; thence to Kane Springs Junction and to Indio. There were comparatively few snakes DOR on the coastal side of the mountains, indicating that the season is already past its peak on this side. It was dusk at Julian so the daylight driving will counted this far.

1 C. Ruber S. |COR| Shady Dell 6:23 PM, fields and trees. Sun had just set (in this mountain valley). Hit him in the tail myself.
1 Gopher S. |DOR| Sutherland, brush.

Reached Julian at 7:12. Dusk. Caught a Blainvillii 2 mi. W. of Scissors Crossing on the road at 7:30. Almost dark. Think this is the darkest I have ever seen this species active.

Scissors Crossing at 7:35, breezy and cool, 68° Still not quite dark

(Continued on Feb. 3rd)

Saturday, June 10, 1939

This morning I was awakened at 4:30 by the failure of the ventilating fan in my room. The support broke and the fan blades hit the side with a violent clatter which startled me out of a sound sleep. As I couldn't sleep any more I decided to cruise the roads to see what's doing early, before the birds clear the corpses.

Got started at 4:50 warm and a little breezy. Just sunup. Toads still calling. Took the Palm Springs, Whitewater, Edom loop. Nothing seen alive, not a single lizard. Back at Indo at 6:55. Now quite warm, some breeze. 64 miles for this drive.

1 Gopher M. |DOR| Indio, fields (saved head)
1 Arizona S. |DOR| 3 mi. SE. of Cathedral City, rocks; sandy desert.

Sunday, June 11, 1939

This morning we started from Indio for Trona at 9:15 very hot.These notes are evening written in the Trona restaurant at 4:50 P.M. Very hot outside.

Dips were very plentiful playing and scouting on the road at Bistra Junction, Myona, Dry Camp, and Edom (Riverside Co.) They curl their tails up to avoid the heat of the pavement. Callies and dips were seen at Rino and Garnet; dips at 29 Palms Junction.

Monday, June 19, 1939

Went to the Reptile Club tonight. Perkins gave a good talk on his South American Trip.

Reddick, Woodall, Organbright, and several out of town people were there. Reddick says Xantusia Riversiana doesn't come out at night. On San Clemente they are under rocks; on Santa Barbara under ice plant. Says a gopher snake was killed by marines on San Clemente.

Tuesday, June 20, 1939

Chas. Shaw worked today. Miscellaneous work tonight. Discovered today that the thermometer I have been using in error. This will require a change in all readings so far this year.

Impossible to tell when the thermometer went haywire. The calibrations were made by White this day. Tycos thermometer reads 1 high at 90°F. Correct 50° to 80° inclusive.

Bath thermometer (one I have been using) reads 17° low at 60° to 80° and 16° low above. I have been making a correction of 20 which makes the net error 15° and 14°.

Both thermometers were in use on the night of June 17 and an error of at least 11° was evident that night. But the error was not present to the same degree all spring as can be seen by some of the results. Adding 14° or 15° to the readings (for example on the Bakersfield trip) gives impossible figures.

Left Tuscon east bound at 10:10 clear, warm, cloudy to the north. Collected lizards for a short time at the Pinal-Cochise Co. Line. Got 2 snakes from a bailer at Benson. Went down to Tombstone, Bisbee, Lowell, Warren, and Nasco. Cloudy and some rain.

1 Red Racer L. |DOR| 15 mi. S.W. of Bisbee, scattered brush.

Started the evening drive at 7:15. Some rain some lightning. Worked over to the foothills of the Huachucas and back to Nasco, Don Luis and Bisbee. Temp 82° down to 74°. Saw only one snake and he got away.

Miles today 193; evening drive 43 miles, 2 hr.s 22 minutes. A very poor day.

Thursday, July 20, 1939

Started for LA this morning at 6:40 and arrived at UCLA at 10:05.

A foggy day early; later clear and warm.

Traveled too fast and may have missed some specimens so don't count mileage.

1 Cal King L |DOR| grass, La Costa
1 Cal King L |DOR| grass, Agra
Good strip-light below.
1 Boyles King L |DOR| San Mateo
1 Oreganus S |DOR| San Clemente

Talked snakes and such like with Cowles. He is much wrapped up with temperature studies; and he and his students are doing much fine work. He is not interested in taxonomy. I made notes on the UCLA collection. They keep only a few specimens of each species. I borrowed Trimorphodon, Rhinocheilus and a few Phyllorhynchus.

Left books to be bound; then to RR Commission. Left there at 5 P.M. and got home at 8. Nothing seen but count no miles. Cowles told me SH Walker was bitten by Cinereons and Chuck Bogerta brother by Cerastes. Had a hard time.

Tuesday, October 24, 1939

Out to dinner tonight.
Chas worked today.

Field notes by Gander:

At about 11:30 a.m. I got out of my car on the Lyons Valley road near where it intersects the boundary of the Cleveland National Forest and walked a few steps to a shallow stream bed. There I started a a striped racer which rushed up the cow bank into the branches of a live oak; then quickly wound its way to the top about 30 ft. up. Half an hour later and about a mile father along on the road toward Barrett, I saw another striped racer on the road ahead. I drove up and stopped along side, then opened the car door and stuck out one foot and put it on the racer's tail. He flattened himself (perhaps she) to the ground but made no other move until I reached down and picked it up. The snake made no attempt to bite and was rather calm for a racer. The snake ere about the same size, near three feet somewhere.

Notes:

Szlyna

Not sure on "cow" bank?
